-- South African Stocks Climb for 5th Day in Six; Kelly, Jubilee, Spar Move
-- B y   C a r l i   L o u r e n s
-- 2010-10-04T16:36:16Z
-- http://www.bloomberg.com/news/2010-10-04/south-african-stocks-bhp-billiton-kumba-iron-ore-shares-move.html
South Africa’s  FTSE/JSE Africa All
Share Index  rose for the fifth session in six, gaining 28.24, or
0.1 percent, to 29,294.97 at the 5 p.m. close in Johannesburg.
The following were among the most active stocks in the South
African market today.  JSE Ltd.  (JSE SJ) climbed 1.99 rand, or 2.8 percent, to
74.29 rand, the highest since January 2008. The operator of
South Africa’s stock exchange was rated “buy” in new coverage
at Deutsche Bank, which set a 12-month price estimate of 80 rand
a share.  Jubilee Platinum Plc  (JBL SJ) declined for the first time
in seven sessions, falling 10 cents, or 2.6 percent, to 3.80
rand. Jubilee’s loss for the year through June narrowed to 2.23
million pounds ($3.5 million) from 4.2 million pounds a year
earlier.  Kelly Group Ltd.  (KEL SJ) dropped the most in more than
three weeks, retreating 18 cents, or 3.9 percent, to 4.50 rand.
Per-share earnings fell by 35 percent to 45 percent in the
fiscal year through Sept. 30 from a year earlier, the personnel
agency said.  Spar Group Ltd.  (SPP SJ), the food and liquor retailer,
fell for the second session from a record, slipping 1.82 rand,
or 2 percent, to 89.13 rand. Spar’s recommendation was lowered
to “sell” from “hold” at Investec Plc.  Steinhoff International Holdings Ltd.  (SHF SJ) rose for a
seventh day, the longest streak of gains since March, climbing
30 cents, or 1.5 percent, to 21 rand. PPR SA is in talks to sell
its Conforama furniture chain to Steinhoff, the Wall Street
Journal reported Oct. 1, citing an unidentified person familiar
with the matter.  To contact the reporter on this story:
